<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="components" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Course Components</title>
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Video Lessons</title>
      <p>Within each lesson, you will be given a reading assignment and example videos.  
        The example videos have short quiz problems to help you gauge your understanding 
        of the basics of the concept. These video lessons are part of your completion score 
        in this course. These quiz problems in the videos are used to check understanding 
        of what was read and watched.  The video quizzes are graded on completion, and you 
        must complete at least 19 of them to earn a passing grade.  While these assignments 
        have due dates, they can be submitted late, and the last day to submit them for 
        credit is Monday, August 3, 2026.</p>
  </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Written Practice Assignments</title>
      <p> Within each lesson in this course, you will be asked to practice the lesson material 
        prior to taking the quizzes or the assessment. These assignments are meant to ensure 
        you have a fundamental understanding of the material. Each written practice (WP) must 
        be completed by a specific date, but they can be started at any time. You will be 
        provided with solutions for these so that you can check your work. These assignments 
        are graded on completion. While working through these assignments, it would benefit 
        you to take notes and keep your work organized. This will help you review material 
        and prepare for the assessments. Also, as you are working, ask questions. Write down 
        problems or questions that you have, and meet with a tutor or schedule an appointment 
        with your instructor. If you do not understand something, ask.</p>
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Practice Opportunities</title>
      <p>In Canvas, you will find practice quizzes that will provide some practice for each of the 
        learning outcomes. Each practice quiz can be completed as many times as needed to practice 
        the material. In addition to these quizzes, it is highly recommended that you work through 
        some of the problems at the end of the Flatworld sections. This will help in solidifying 
        foundational knowledge. Flatworld also has additional videos and practice sets that can be
        used for further study. In each of the introduction pages, I have also added links to different
        CheckIt banks that you can use to review concepts. <em>The practice materials are just that, for 
          practice.  These assignments do not affect your grade and these are not included in the 
          module time expectations.</em>
    </p>
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Mastery Quizzes</title>
      <p> We will have 2-3 mastery quizzes per week.  Each quiz will cover one of the learning outcomes 
        of the content. The quiz will be a first look at what you understand about that concept. These 
        quizzes will be graded based on the mastery rubric and returned within 24 hours. If you score 
        an M on a quiz, you are done and ready to move on to the next topic. If you score a P on the 
        quiz, you can either keep this score or revise your work to try to earn an M. The corrections 
        will be due five weekdays after the quiz date.  If you earn an R or N on the quiz, then you will 
        be allowed a retake.  You will be given some practice problems, asked to complete a tutoring 
        appointment to go over the concepts in that module, and you will be given a new version of the 
        quiz. You will be allowed up to five weekdays to complete a retake quiz.  The quizzes and 
        retakes are done through Canvas. You will have a set time limit for each quiz and will need 
        digitizing materials nearby to upload your work. The time limit posted includes about 5 minutes 
        to digitize and upload your work. Please watch your time limit.  If the time limit expires and 
        you do not upload any work in Gradescope, you will earn an N on the quiz and need to retake it. 
        Work submitted outside of Canvas or Gradescope will not be accepted.</p>
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Tutoring</title>
      <p>I require that students complete a minimum of 4 tutoring appointments during the semester. 
        These appointments will appear in Canvas.  There are seven tutoring windows in the course.  
        If you have earned an M or P on all of the quizzes in that tutoring window, you will automatically 
        earn credit for that tutoring window.  If you have earned an R or N on any quiz during that 
        tutoring window, you will need to complete a tutoring appointment.  The tutoring appointment 
        must be scheduled and attended for a minimum of 30 minutes, one-on-one with a tutor, either 
        in-person or through Zoom. <em>Drop-in tutoring sessions will NOT count towards these 
          appointments.</em> These appointments need to be scheduled and completed through the 
          Math Services Appointment Tutoring (link is in Canvas) to earn credit. Students should use 
          their UA credentials to create and attend appointments. </p>
          <p>If there are questions about concepts, tutors are available to help with understanding. 
            In addition, as this is an asynchronous course, there are no set meetings between students; 
            however, discussion of math concepts is essential to improving mathematical vocabulary and 
            understanding, as well as creating inquiry. These appointments are graded on completion.</p>
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Revisions and Retakes</title>
      <p>If you score an M on a quiz, you are done and ready to move on to the next topic. If 
        you score a P on the quiz, you can either keep this score or revise your work to try to 
        earn an M. The revisions have set due dates and will not be accepted after that time. 
        <em>All of the work for the revisions must be submitted in Canvas to receive 
          credit.</em> If you earn an R or N on the quiz, then you will be allowed a retake. You will 
        be required to do some practice problems, complete a tutoring appointment to go over the 
        concepts in that module, and you will be given a new version of the quiz. The retakes have set 
        due dates and should be submitted through Canvas. <em>All of the work for the revisions must 
          be submitted in Canvas to receive credit.</em></p>
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Assessments</title>
      <p>We will have three assessments and a final during the semester. You will have the opportunity 
        to assess many of the outcomes up to 3 times. If you are not ready for a particular concept, 
        no worries, leave it blank and try it on the following assessment.  If you are away during an 
        assessment for university- or military-sponsored events, you will need to schedule a time before 
        leaving to complete the assessment. If you miss an assessment window without making previous 
        arrangements, you can attempt mastery on the following assessment or on the final (depending on
        which topics are available in the next assessment). All assessments are proctored, so you will 
        need to <em>set up your proctor in the first week of class</em>. You will need to schedule your 
        assessments through UAF Testing Services at least 3 days in advance of the testing window, so 
        you will need to plan accordingly. Assessments will be available during the windows as outlined 
        below.  Students who have not scheduled these appointments or have not requested materials by 
        the deadline will miss the chance to take that assessment. If a student is outside Fairbanks, 
        appointments with the proctor/testing center at their location must be made in addition to the 
        request for materials from UAF Testing Services.</p>
    </paragraphs>
  
</section>